---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-korea', text: 'Leaving Korean Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'nhis-considerations', text: 'NHIS Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'koreaCoverage', header: 'Korea Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', usNetwork: 'Strong', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', koreaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '₩220,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', usNetwork: 'Excellent', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', koreaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '₩250,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', usNetwork: 'Good', globalNetwork: 'Strong', koreaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '₩210,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Samsung Life', usNetwork: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Limited', koreaCoverage: 'Included', price: '₩180,000/mo' },
  { provider: 'Hanwha Life', usNetwork: 'Limited', globalNetwork: 'Limited', koreaCoverage: 'Included', price: '₩170,000/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for South Korean Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Korean expats. Find coverage for the US, Europe, and other destinations while understanding NHIS implications."
  headline="Best Insurance for Korean Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="South Korea has excellent healthcare through NHIS. Here's how to stay covered when you work or study abroad—and understand your Korean healthcare options."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/south-korean-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Korean expats include students, tech professionals, business executives, and families. The US is a major destination, particularly for students and tech workers. Understanding NHIS rules when abroad is important. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Korean expats. Strong US networks, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Top-tier service.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong European networks.</li>
    <li><strong>Samsung Life:</strong> Major Korean insurer with international products. Familiar brand, Korea included.</li>
    <li><strong>Hanwha Life:</strong> Korean insurer with some international coverage. Familiar service.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="US Student and Professional Coverage"
    description="Many Korean students and professionals work in US tech companies. University insurance and employer coverage may have limitations. Understand your coverage—supplement if needed."
    buttonText="Get US Coverage Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-korea">Leaving Korean Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    South Korea's National Health Insurance Service (NHIS) provides excellent coverage. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>NHIS Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    NHIS covers all Korean residents with comprehensive healthcare at affordable copays. The system is excellent—world-class facilities at reasonable costs. When you leave Korea, NHIS rules change.
  </p>

  <h3>NHIS Abroad</h3>
  <p>
    NHIS doesn't cover healthcare outside Korea. Emergency treatment abroad isn't covered. You need separate international insurance for healthcare in your destination country.
  </p>

  <h3>Maintaining NHIS</h3>
  <p>
    Koreans abroad can sometimes maintain NHIS membership for coverage during Korea visits. Rules vary based on duration abroad and registration status. Voluntary continuation may be possible.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Korean Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private insurers (Samsung Life, Hanwha, Kyobo) offer various products. Some have international options, but global networks are typically limited compared to international specialists.
  </p>

  <h2 id="nhis-considerations">NHIS Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Understanding NHIS rules helps plan your coverage:
  </p>

  <h3>Registration Changes</h3>
  <p>
    When you leave Korea long-term, your NHIS status may change. De-registration affects your coverage eligibility. Understand the rules before you leave.
  </p>

  <h3>Returning to Korea</h3>
  <p>
    When you return, NHIS coverage typically resumes. There may be re-registration requirements. Short visits don't affect your NHIS status, but long-term returns require proper registration.
  </p>

  <h3>Voluntary Continuation</h3>
  <p>
    Some Koreans abroad can maintain NHIS through voluntary continuation. This keeps coverage for Korea visits. Premiums continue based on your last Korean income.
  </p>

  <h3>Military Service Implications</h3>
  <p>
    Korean men have military service obligations. Time abroad affects these. Healthcare coverage intersects with military service status in some cases.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Healthcare Quality Expectations</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Korean healthcare is world-class with short wait times and high technology. International insurance should match these expectations—don't accept inferior coverage abroad.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Korean expats. Strong US networks critical for students and tech professionals. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 service with Korean support available through Asia operations. Korea coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats in the US and elsewhere wanting reliable comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent worldwide networks. Service quality matches Korean expectations for efficiency and responsiveness.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium quality. Korea coverage available as add-on.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean professionals who want top-tier coverage matching Korean standards.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks in Europe and adequate coverage elsewhere. Good value for comprehensive protection.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats seeking good value, especially in European destinations.
  </p>

  <h3>Samsung Life</h3>
  <p>
    Samsung Life is one of Korea's largest insurers and offers international products. Familiar brand, Korean service, Korea coverage included. International networks are more limited than global specialists.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats who prefer familiar Korean service with seamless home coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Hanwha Life</h3>
  <p>
    Hanwha Life offers some international coverage options. Familiar Korean service, Korea coverage included. International networks are limited compared to global insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats who want familiar service and primarily need Korea coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Get quotes from multiple providers. Consider US network strength if that's your destination—many Korean expats are in the US for school or work."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Korean expats have specific destination patterns:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Large Korean community, especially in California (Los Angeles) and New York. Many students and tech professionals. US healthcare is expensive—comprehensive coverage essential. Korean-speaking doctors available in major communities.
  </p>

  <h3>Japan</h3>
  <p>
    Close neighbor with significant Korean community. Japanese health insurance covers employed residents. International insurance covers transitions and provides options beyond Japanese coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>China</h3>
  <p>
    Business connections mean many Koreans work in China. Healthcare quality varies by city. International insurance ensures access to quality facilities, especially international hospitals.
  </p>

  <h3>Europe</h3>
  <p>
    Growing Korean presence, especially in Germany and UK. EU countries have public healthcare for legal residents. International insurance supplements local coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does NHIS cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. NHIS only covers healthcare in Korea. You need separate international insurance for coverage in your destination country.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep NHIS while abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Voluntary continuation may be possible. This maintains coverage for Korea visits. Check with NHIS about your specific situation and requirements.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is US university insurance enough?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">University insurance meets minimum requirements but may have limitations. Review coverage carefully—supplemental international insurance provides better protection.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about US employer insurance?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">US employer insurance typically provides good coverage while employed. It ends with employment—international insurance provides continuity during job transitions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Samsung Life or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Samsung Life offers Korean familiarity and includes Korea. Cigna has stronger global networks, especially in the US. Choose based on destination and preferences.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Korean support available?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Korean insurers offer full Korean service. International insurers have varying Korean capability. In the US, areas with Korean communities have Korean-speaking providers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Korean expats need comprehensive international insurance—NHIS doesn't cover you abroad. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for strong US and global coverage. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium service matching Korean expectations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Samsung Life</strong> and <strong>Hanwha Life</strong> suit those who prefer familiar Korean service with integrated home coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Understand NHIS rules before leaving. Consider maintaining NHIS for Korea visits while having international insurance for your residence country.
  </p>

</PageShell>
